Same as Subsets — return all possible subsets — but now nums may contain duplicates, and the result must contain no duplicate subsets.
          Input: nums = [1,2,2]
          Output: [[], [1], [1,2], [1,2,2], [2], [2,2]]
          
          NOT allowed: [[], [1], [1,2], [1,2], [1,2,2], [2], [2], [2,2]]
                                      ↑ two [1,2]s, two [2]s — from choosing "first 2" vs "second 2"

/*
 * Problem: Subsets II (duplicates in input) ⭐
 * Pattern: Backtracking + sorted-adjacent skip
 * Time: O(n·2ⁿ), Space: O(n) path + output
 * Key insight: sort FIRST — duplicates must be adjacent for the skip to see them
 * THE RULE: if(i > start && nums[i]==nums[i-1]) continue;
 *   i > start  → previous equal was MY LOOP's sibling round → its subtree covered everything → skip
 *   i == start → previous equal is PARENT's choice, sitting in path → stacking [2,2] → allowed
 *   One line: "bhai ne liya toh mat le, baap ne liya toh le le"
 * Photograph rule: result.add(new ArrayList<>(path)) — parchi nahi, photo
 */



static void backtrack(int[] nums, int start, List<Integer> path, List<List<Integer>> result){
	result.add(new ArrayList<>(path));
	
	for(int i= start; i<nums.length; i++){
		if(i > start && nums[i] == nums[i-1]) continue;
		path.add(nums[i]);
		backtrack(nums, i+1, path, result);
		path.remove(path.size()-1);
	}
}

static List<List<Integer>> subsetsWithDup(int[] nums){
	int n = nums.length;
	Arrays.sort(nums);
	List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
	List<Integer> path = new ArrayList<>();
	backtrack(nums, 0, path, result);
	return result;
}


          
          
